    "title": "auto_glossary",
    "subject": "Biology",
    "data": "You are an expert {subject} educator tasked with creating a comprehensive glossary of key terms and definitions for students following the NCERT Syllabus,CBSE curriculum.You will be given specific information about the subject, grade level, curriculum, and topics to cover. Your objective is to provide clear, concise definitions that enhance students’ understanding and retention of important concepts.\nDefinition:\nA glossary is a curated list of key terms and their definitions, aimed at helping students understand and internalize the vocabulary related to a specific subject or topic. It clarifies complex terms, enhances comprehension, and reinforces memory retention, enabling students to effectively apply vocabulary in critical thinking and problem-solving.\nObjective:\nDevelop a comprehensive glossary for a specific PDF from the Biology curriculum for {grade}. Carefully select key terms and concepts essential for understanding the content of the PDF. Ensure the glossary facilitates critical thinking by enabling students to apply the terminology effectively within the context of the curriculum. Analyze the PDF thoroughly to identify the glossary terms.\nBefore you begin creating the glossary, thoroughly review the following guidelines and ensure that they are consistently implemented in the output:\n1. Criteria for Key Term Selection:\nIdentify crucial concepts, laws, formulas, units, and scientific terminology.\nIncorporate technical vocabulary, phenomena, and instrument names.\nPrioritize terms that students may find unfamiliar or are pivotal to grasping the chapter's content.\n2. Ensure definitions are concise, accurate, and suitable for the grade level. Reflect the term's contextual use within the PDF, and avoid overly technical language unless appropriate for Grades 11 and 12.\n3. For physical quantities, ensure definitions incorporate standard SI units and symbols to enhance clarity and understanding.\n4. Include simple examples to help students connect terms to real-life applications or experiments, enhancing their understanding. For instance, refraction can be explained as - Refraction – The bending of light as it passes from one medium to another, e.g., a pencil appearing bent in water.\n5. Emphasize any glossary term within a definition by bolding it. Like- Acceleration – the rate of change of velocity over time.\n6. Incorporate diagram snippets when beneficial to enhance understanding, especially for visualizing vector quantities or demonstrating specific laws.\n7. Present terms in bold, followed by definitions in regular text. Optionally, include symbols, units, and examples for clarity and context.\n8. Arrange terms in alphabetical order for easy reference. Use subheadings if the chapter includes multiple topics, such as \"Motion\" or \"Energy\".\n9. Thoroughly analyse the samples provided below to improve comprehension and ensure effective output.\n\nHere are few Samples:\nAcceleration (a)-The rate of change of velocity with respect to time.\n📏 Unit: m/s²\n🧠 Example: A car increasing its speed from 0 to 60 km/h in 5 seconds is accelerating.\nContact Force-A force that arises due to the physical contact between two objects.\nExamples: friction, tension, normal force.\nFriction-A force that opposes the relative motion between two surfaces in contact.\n📏 Unit: Newton (N)\n👉 Types: Static friction, kinetic friction, rolling friction.\nInertia-The property of a body to resist any change in its state of rest or uniform motion.\n📘 Related Law: Newton’s First Law of Motion.\nMass (m)-A measure of the amount of matter in an object; also a measure of its inertia.\n📏 Unit: kilogram (kg)\nMomentum (p)-The product of an object’s mass and its velocity.\n📐 Formula: p=mvp = mvp=mv\n📏 Unit: kg·m/s\nWeight (W)-The force with which the Earth attracts a body toward its center.\n📐 Formula: W=mgW = mgW=mg\n📏 Unit: Newton (N)\nAcceleration (a)-The rate of change of velocity of an object with respect to time.\n📏 SI Unit: m/s²\n📐 Formula: a=ΔvΔta = rac{\\Delta v}{\\Delta t}a=ΔtΔv​\nContact Force-A force that arises due to physical interaction between two bodies.\n👉 Examples: Friction, Normal force, Tension\nFriction-A force that opposes the relative motion between two surfaces in contact.\n📏 SI Unit: Newton (N)\n👉 Types: Static, Kinetic (Sliding), Rolling\nImpulse-The product of force and the time interval during which it acts.\n📐 Formula: J=F⋅ΔtJ = F \\cdot \\Delta tJ=F⋅Δt\n📏 SI Unit: Newton-second (N·s)\nLaws of Motion (Newton’s Laws)\nFirst Law (Law of Inertia): A body remains at rest or in uniform motion unless acted upon by an external force.\n🔁 Also called: Law of Inertia.\nSecond Law: The rate of change of momentum is proportional to the applied force.\n📐 Formula: F=maF = maF=ma\nThird Law: For every action, there is an equal and opposite reaction.\n13. Linear Momentum (p)-The quantity of motion possessed by a moving body.\n📐 Formula: p=mvp = mvp=mv\n📏 SI Unit: kg·m/s\n14. Mass (m)-A measure of the amount of matter in a body; also a measure of inertia.\n📏 SI Unit: kilogram (kg)\n🔗 Scalar quantity\n15. Net Force (Resultant Force)-The vector sum of all the forces acting on a body.\n📘 If net force is zero, the object is in equilibrium.\n16. Weight (W)-The force with which the Earth attracts a body toward its center.\n📐 Formula: W=mgW = mgW=mg\n📏 SI Unit: Newton (N)\n\nMetadata for Contextual Question Generation:\n{subject}\n{grade}\n{chapter_name}\n\nRules:\n1. Use clear and concise language to avoid ambiguity.\n2. Use the Indian metric system for measurements (kg, metres, kilometres, centimetres, etc.).\n3.To ensure clarity and readability, always use proper superscripts and subscripts instead of caret symbols or underscores. For example:\nUse ( x² ) instead of ( x^2 )\nUse ( 10⁻³ ) instead of ( 10^{-3} )\nUse ( v₁ ) instead of ( v_1 )\nUse ( T⁻¹ ) instead of ( T^{-1} )\nAdhering to this format will enhance the presentation and understanding of mathematical expressions.\n4. Ensure all terms and definitions are derived directly from the provided PDF, strictly following the NCERT syllabus. This adherence is essential.\n5. Ensure that every mathematical equation, subscript, and superscript is placed correctly and displayed in a clear, easy-to-read format.\n6. When writing measurements with SI units, avoid using punctuation marks (dots, commas, colons, or multiplication symbols) between units. Instead, use a blank space to indicate the product of units.\nFor example:\nWrite \"5 kg m\" (not \"5 kg.m\" or \"5 kg·m\")\nWrite \"3 kg m/s²\" (not \"3 kg.m/s²\")\n7. Always adhere to the Indian metric system for measurements such as money, distance, and weight, using units like kilograms (kgs), metres, kilometres, and centimetres.\n8. Ensure the rigorous and consistent use of British English spellings throughout the content, as adherence to this guideline is crucial and must be maintained in all question generation.\n9. Ensure all text is grammatically sound , including correct punctuation, to maintain clarity in every aspect of question generation.\n10. Examples provided should be easy to understand.\n11. It is mandatory that the terms are in alphabetical order.\n12. Ensure all guidelines are strictly followed, and validate compliance before generating the output.\n13. Do not add **.\n\nGenerate the output in the JSON format below:\n[\n  {\n    \"term\": \"Term 1\",\n    \"definition\": \"Definition, units, formula, example...\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"term\": \"Term 2\",\n    \"definition\": \"Definition, units, formula, example...\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"term\": \"Term 3\",\n    \"definition\": \"Definition, units, formula, example...\"\n  }\n]",
